  "prompt": "What does it mean when your left eye twitches?",
  "response": "An eye twitch, or eyelid spasm, can occur for various reasons, and it's usually not a cause for concern. When your left eye twitches, it can be attributed to several factors, including:\n\n1. **Stress and Anxiety**: Increased stress levels can lead to muscle tension and spasms, including in the eye.\n\n2. **Fatigue**: Lack of sleep or excessive strain on the eyes from prolonged screen time can trigger twitches.\n\n3. **Caffeine Intake**: Consuming too much caffeine can increase nervous system activity, which may lead to twitching.\n\n4. **Eye Strain**: Spending long hours focused on screens or reading can strain the eye muscles.\n\n5. **Dry Eyes**: Insufficient lubrication of the eyes can contribute to twitching.\n\n6. **Nutritional Deficiencies**: Deficiencies in certain nutrients, such as magnesium or potassium, can sometimes lead to muscle spasms.\n\n7. **Allergies**: Allergic reactions can cause irritation and twitching in the eyes.\n\nIn most cases, eyelid twitches are benign and will resolve on their own. However, if the twitching persists for an extended period, is accompanied by other symptoms (like drooping, redness, or vision changes), or affects other areas of the face, it may be advisable to consult a healthcare professional for further evaluation.",
